  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I find the URL of a picture?",
  "response": "To find the URL of a picture, follow these steps based on the device and browser you are using:\n\n### On a Computer (Desktop/Laptop)\n\n#### Using a Web Browser:\n1. **Right-click on the Image**: Navigate to the image you want, then right-click on it.\n2. **Select \"Copy image address\"**: In the context menu that appears, choose \"Copy image address\" (or \"Copy image URL\" depending on the browser). This copies the URL of the image to your clipboard.\n3. **Paste the URL**: You can now paste the URL wherever you need it (e.g., in a document, chat, etc.) by right-clicking and selecting \"Paste\" or using `Ctrl + V` (Windows) or `Command + V` (Mac).\n\n#### Using the Address Bar (if applicable):\n1. **Open the image in a new tab**: If the image is linked to another page, right-click on the image, and select \u201cOpen image in new tab\u201d or \u201cView image\u201d (the wording may vary by browser).\n2. **Copy from the Address Bar**: Once the image opens in a new tab, you can copy the URL from the address bar.\n\n### On Mobile Devices\n\n#### Using a Mobile Browser:\n1. **Tap and Hold the Image**: Press and hold on the image until a menu appears.\n2. **Select \"Copy Image Address\" or \"Open Image in New Tab\"**: If your browser supports it, tap on \"Copy image address.\" If not, you might need to open the image in a new tab.\n3. **Paste the URL**: Similar to desktops, paste the URL wherever you need it.\n\n### Note\n- Some images may not allow you to copy their URL due to copyright or privacy settings.\n- URLs of images may be temporary or may change over time, especially on social media platforms and image-hosting sites.\n\nIf you\u2019re trying to find the URL of an image that is not available publicly, or is embedded in a way that blocks access, it may not be possible to retrieve the URL directly.",
